<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTY READIES BATTLE PLAN AGAINST GYPSY MOTH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LORI GRANGE, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The discovery in San Diego County this year of several gypsy moths, 
tree-destroying pests with voracious appetites, has prompted agriculture 
officials to increase trapping and surveillance of the insect and consider 
spraying pesticide. 
</P>
<P>
About six male gypsy moths have been found in San Diego County in 1989. One 
insect was trapped in Valley Center, near the intersection of Cole Grade Road 
and Valley Center Road. Five others, including one trapped last weekend, have 
been caught in La Mesa, near the intersection of Spring Street and California 
94. 
</P>
<P>
The pest, which can eat up to a square foot of leaves daily, was eradicated 
from the Mission Valley area in 1985, after trappings of hundreds of the 
insects throughout California in the early 1980s led to statewide pesticide 
spraying, said Kathleen Thuner, county agricultural commissioner. 
</P>
<P>
"Finding one sort of marshals your forces. But when you get more than one in an 
area, that signifies that there may be potential infestation," Thuner said. "We 
still don't know if spraying will be needed." 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Monitoring Traps 
</P>
<P>
Agriculture officials have increased trapping in La Mesa and Valley Center, and 
are monitoring traps daily in Spring Valley, Ocean Beach and Del Mar, where 
three moths were found last year. Officials are searching primarily for gypsy 
egg masses, which can hold as many as 1,000 eggs, Thuner said. 
</P>
<P>
If the small, tan, hair-covered eggs of the moth are found, officials may 
consider spraying bacillus thuringiensis, an organic pesticide that kills the 
larvae, next spring. 
</P>
<P>
Found mostly in northeastern states, gypsy moths during their caterpillar stage 
feed on more than 300 varieties of plants and shrubs. They can also defoliate 
and destroy many types of trees, including avocado, lemon, pine and evergreen 
trees. 
</P>
<P>
"The moth has an appetite for just about anything with a leaf on it," Thuner 
said. 
</P>
<P>
The adult male gypsy moth has feathery antennas with dark wings and a 1 
1/2-inch wingspan, she said. The female insects are white, with a wingspan of 
about 2 inches. 
</P>
</TEXT>
