<P>
EXILED CLERIC SEEKS IRANIAN PRESIDENCY, CAN'T GET PASSPORT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
PARIS 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The man considered the spiritual leader of Shiite Muslims in Europe said Monday 
he wants to run for president of Iran but is being refused a valid passport to 
return to his homeland. 
</P>
<P>
The Ayatollah Mehdi Rouhani said he wrote a letter June 10 to Interior Minister 
Ali Akbar Mohtashemi to inform him of his bid for the presidency. He said that 
on Friday, he was instructed to go the Iranian Embassy to fill out the proper 
forms, but on Monday he was told he could not get his passport validated. 
</P>
<P>
Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani is the only official candidate in the 
July 28 election. Wednesday is the last day to file as a candidate. 
</P>
<P>
Rouhani, 53, has spent 25 years in Europe and is a resident of France. He said 
he has been unable to get his Iranian passport validated for four or five 
years. 
</P>
