<P>
Metro; Part 2; Page 7; Column 5; Op-Ed Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
796 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
GIAMATTI SHOULD CALL IN THE 'BULLPEN' TO JUDGE ROSE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALAN M. DERSHOWITZ, Alan M. Dershowitz teaches at Harvard Law School and 
writes a syndicated column. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Pete Rose will probably strike out in his attempt to get the federal courts to 
prevent baseball's Commissioner A. Bartlett Giamatti from deciding his fate. 
But "Charlie Hustle" does have a point in arguing that Giamatti may have 
compromised his objectivity when he wrote a letter to a federal judge in 
Cincinnati, commenting on Ronald Peters' cooperation with the baseball 
investigation. 
</P>
<P>
Peters, a convicted drug trafficker, was facing a stiff sentence. Giamatti 
wrote to the sentencing judge, advising him of Peters' cooperation, calling it 
"significant and truthful." The obvious purpose of the letter was to reward 
Peters for his help in the baseball investigation. 
</P>
<P>
In publicly declaring Peters' damning testimony against Rose to be "truthful" 
-- without having heard from Rose himself -- Giamatti appears to have prejudged 
the credibility of a major witness. This is simply unfair. Rose has essentially 
called Peters a liar, and Rose's lawyers have alleged that the "betting slips" 
Peters has provided to the media -- and presumably to the commissioner -- were 
altered. Since Peters sought to trade his information for favorable treatment, 
there is good reason to approach its veracity with several shakers full of 
salt. It may well be believable -- especially if it is corroborated by 
objective evidence -- but it certainly cannot be believed simply because Peters 
says it is true. 
</P>
<P>
If Giamatti is the judge and jury in the Rose case -- as he claims he is -- 
then he should not be making public (or even private) assessments of the 
credibility of a crucial witness, before that witness has been subjected to the 
truth-testing process of confrontation and cross-examination. Would Giamatti 
really be open to the possibility of now disbelieving Peters? If so, would he 
have to write a correcting letter to the judge? 
</P>
<P>
Giamatti is not bound, of course, by the provisions of the Bill of Rights, or 
even by the common-law system of determining truth. Baseball is a law unto 
itself. It has a unique status as our national pastime, a status recognized by 
its exemption from antitrust laws that are applicable to other big-time sports. 
But the public has the right to expect that major league baseball will be fair. 
</P>
<P>
There is nothing inherently wrong with the commissioner of baseball expressing 
his opinion on the value of a witness' cooperation. Nor is there anything wrong 
with him writing to a sentencing judge on behalf of a convicted defendant 
awaiting sentence, even if that letter was part of a deal for that defendant's 
cooperation with his investigation. Prosecutors do that all the time. 
</P>
<P>
And that is the crux of the issue. Giamatti seems to be acting more like a 
prosecutor -- a careful and fair one, to be sure -- than like a judge. The 
investigation appears similar to grand jury inquiries being conducted by an 
earnest prosecutor determined to learn the truth. 
</P>
<P>
But under the American system of justice, a grand jury only indicts; it does 
not convict. An independent judiciary, not involved in the investigation, 
passes the ultimate judgment of guilt or innocence only after hearing both 
sides. This "adversary system of justice" is widely regarded as the best 
protection against bias, both conscious and unconscious. 
</P>
<P>
Whether Giamatti eventually wins or loses the federal court suit filed against 
him by Rose -- and I predict he will win -- he should take Rose's charges of 
prejudgment seriously. In a high-profile case like this one, it is important 
that justice not only be done, but also appear to be done. Of course, Giamatti 
must believe that he can still be fair. And he may even be right. But Pete Rose 
fans will never be satisfied if the commissioner relies on Peters' testimony 
after having publicly prejudged his credibility. 
</P>
<P>
Giamatti should proceed with his investigation. If, after hearing Rose's side 
of the story, he concludes that Rose is guilty of betting, then he should issue 
his report as an "indictment." That indictment should then be presented to a 
completely neutral panel of distinguished arbitrators who had nothing to do 
with the investigation. That panel, which could include such luminaries as 
retired Supreme Court Justices Arthur A. Goldberg Jr. and Lewis Powell and 
others of similar unimpeachable integrity, would make the ultimate decision. 
They would hear both sides of the case, make credibility determinations about 
the witnesses and render their decision of guilt or innocence. 
</P>
<P>
Under that approach, everything Giamatti has done up to now would be perfectly 
acceptable. He would be a strong advocate for the integrity of baseball. But in 
America, it is regarded as unfair to be both investigator and judge. If and 
when Bart Giamatti releases his indictment of Pete Rose, he should be taken out 
for a relief pitcher. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Opinion 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA062789-0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 75182 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
June 27, 1989, Tuesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part 2; Page 7; Column 4; Op-Ed Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
525 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
EXEC PAY SHOULDN'T BE HOSTAGE TO CONGRESS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARK E. BUCHMAN, Mark E. Buchman, a merchant banker in Century City, was 
president of the Government National Mortgage Assn. (Ginnie Mae) during the 
Reagan Administration. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The February brouhaha over the pay bill is now history. The current 
bloodletting in the House may have run its course with Jim Wright and Tony 
Coelho. The good work done by the Commission on Executive, Legislative and 
Judicial Salaries has gone for naught, mainly because its recommendation was so 
misunderstood by the public -- and Congress wouldn't face up to the issue. 
</P>
<P>
We now see many examples in the Bush Administration where qualified candidates 
will not take or can not keep appointments and where existing officials are 
leaving prematurely to escape onerous employment conditions. Just last week, H. 
Robert Heller, a Federal Reserve governor, announced that he would resign, 
saying he would have been able to stay had Congress approved a pay raise for 
top government officials. 
</P>
<P>
Pay, of course, is not the entire problem or answer. Many non-financial factors 
are involved: challenge, sense of duty and service, the excitement and 
tremendous satisfaction of participating in a policy position in government, 
the knowledge and contacts gained -- these are but a few of the rewards. 
</P>
<P>
Unless we want top federal officials coming just from the wealthier classes of 
our society, we'd better face up to some real problems. Correcting the salary 
scale for senior executive service would be an excellent starter. Right now a 
huge financial sacrifice is involved in going to Washington, one of America's 
most costly places to live. I know because I've done it. A respectable salary 
level should be determined, one that at least doesn't involve outright 
financial losses. There probably always will be, and maybe should be, a 
differential between public and private pay scales, due to the other beneficial 
factors already mentioned. But the gross discrepancies existing at present only 
exacerbate ethical and other temptations. 
</P>
<P>
A key element to the solution is to break the lock Congress has over the salary 
structure of the two other parts of government, the executive and the 
judiciary. Let Congress muck around with its own salary structure and be 
answerable to the electorate. But it is scandalous to hold others hostage to 
the politics of Congress' grandstanding before the voters. Congressmen should 
be well paid and not be permitted to accept any outside income (just as 
executive branch officials are not now permitted to receive any outside direct 
income). 
</P>
<P>
There are many other considerable impediments to government service: the 
voluminous forms to fill out, requiring days of work; the confirmation process 
itself, often drawn out and demeaning to the nominee and his or her family; 
restrictions on post-government employment (not applicable to members of 
Congress, even though they make the rules); virtually total public disclosure 
of one's financial situation and loss of much of the privacy we normally enjoy. 
</P>
<P>
It is said you get what you pay for. In most cases inour society, the men and 
women best suited to run our government are largely turned off by the many 
disincentives of coming to Washington. Let's at least address the pay problem 
with our eyes open and false rhetoric contained. 
</P>
<P>
Would Mr. Smith go to Washington now? 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Opinion 
</P>
</TYPE>
