<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: SCIENCE/TECHNOLOGY; 
</P>
<P>
EMULEX CORP. CONSTRUCTING NEW BUILDING DESPITE SLUGGISH BUSINESS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by David Olmos, Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Emulex Corp. has run out of room at its Harbor Boulevard headquarters in Costa 
Mesa and is erecting a new structure nearby to provide some breathing space for 
its 600 Orange County employees. 
</P>
<P>
The computer products company plans to move its administrative offices into the 
new building when it is completed in early 1990. The 80,000-square-foot, 
two-story facility is under construction at the corner of Harbor and Sunflower 
Avenue in Costa Mesa. 
</P>
<P>
The firm currently operates out of a 214,000-square-foot facility that houses 
its engineering, manufacturing, marketing and administrative operations. 
</P>
<P>
"We're extremely crowded right now," a company spokeswoman said. 
</P>
<P>
Emulex said it will go ahead with the building despite its recent 
acknowledgment that business has been sluggish. 
</P>
<P>
Late last week, the company said earnings for its fourth quarter ended June 2 
will be lower than the $2.8 million reported in the same quarter in 1988. 
Revenue is expected to be between $35 million and $37 million, up from $34.2 
million in the 1988 quarter. 
</P>
<P>
Emulex, which makes computer storage devices and data communications equipment, 
said that competition in its market has become "less favorable" and that sales 
to a major customer will be about $2 million below earlier forecasts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
